# Problem 2

a)
$$
\hat{\beta}=\frac{\sum^n_{i=1}=X_iY_i}{\sum^n_{i=1}=X^2_i} = \frac{\sum^n_{i=1}X_i(X_i\beta+\epsilon_i)}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i} = \frac{\sum^n_{i=1}X_i^2}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i}\beta + \frac{\sum^n_{i=1}X_i\epsilon}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i} =\beta + \frac{\sum^n_{i=1}X_i\epsilon}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i}
$$

Now note that $E(\epsilon|X) = 0$, hence we can derive:

$$
E(\hat{\beta}|X) = \beta + \frac{\sum^n_{i=1}X_i*0}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i}=\beta
$$

And since that $Var(\epsilon|X)=\sigma^2$:
$$
Var(\hat{\beta}|X) = Var(\frac{\sum^n_{i=1}X_i\epsilon}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i}|X)=
\frac{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i\sigma^2}{(\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i)^2}
=\frac{\sigma^2}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i}
$$
b)

$$
\epsilon^*=Y^*-\hat{Y}=X^*\beta + \epsilon - X^**\hat{\beta} = X^*(\beta-\hat{\beta}) + \epsilon
$$

Then:
$$
E(\epsilon^*|X, X^*)=X^*(\beta - \beta) + 0 = 0
$$
$$
Var(\epsilon^*|X, X^*)=Var(X^*\hat{\beta}|X, X^*) + Var(\epsilon|X^*, X) + 2Cov(X^*(\beta-\hat{\beta}), \epsilon|X, X^*)
$$

Note that $2Cov(X^*(\beta-\hat{\beta}), \epsilon|X, X^*) = Cov(\hat{\beta}, \epsilon|X, X^*)$ and epsilons are independent from $\hat{\beta}$. 
Hence:
$$
Var(\epsilon^*|X, X^*)=(X^*)^2Var(\hat{\beta}|X, X^*)+\sigma^2=\frac{(X^*)^2\sigma^2}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i} +\sigma^2=\sigma^2(\frac{(X^*)^2}{\sum^n_{i=1}X^2_i} +1)
$$

c) We have derived variance and expected value of some new observations which are independent from previous, however come from the same model ($\beta$ is the same). So we derived distributional properties of the abnormal returns used in event study approach under $H_0$ which states that there were no significant changes.


