# Problem 3

a)
```{r setup, include=FALSE} 
knitr::opts_chunk$set(warning = FALSE, message = FALSE) 
options(scipen=999)
```
```{r c1}
library(dplyr)
library(tidyquant)
library(purrr)
df <- 
  tq_get('BAS.DE',
         from = '2013/09/16', 
         to = '2024/09/19'
  )%>%
    select(date, close)%>%
    mutate(log_return = log(close) - log(lag(close, 1)))


get_n_moment <- 
  function(n, values){
    obs = length(values)
    sd_est = sd(values)
    avg = mean(values)
    
    sum((values-avg)^n)*(1/((obs-1)*sd_est^n))
  }

data <- df$log_return[-1]

obs <-  nrow(df) - 1

get_n_moment(3, data)/sqrt(6/obs)
```
We can not reject the null on 5% significance, so we can conclude that distribution is symmetric.

b)
```{r c2}
(get_n_moment(4, data)-3)/sqrt(24/obs)
```

Here we can reject the null even on 1% significance, so we have fat tails.

c)
```{r c4}
t_s <- get_n_moment(3, data)/sqrt(6/obs)
t_k <-  (get_n_moment(4, data)-3)/sqrt(24/obs)

(t_s^2)+(t_k^2)
```

And we have chi-square with df=2, hence we can reject the null and conclude that the data is not distributed normally.

d)
```{r c5}
ks.test(data, "pnorm")
```

P-value is less than 0.0001, so we can reject the null, hence log returns are not distributed normally.

e)

Due to summabality of log returns, we can just sum them within each month to get monthly log returns. 

```{r c6}
df_monthly <- 
  df%>%
    mutate(dt_month = lubridate::floor_date(date, "months"))%>%
    group_by(dt_month)%>%
    summarise(month_log_return = sum(log_return, na.rm=TRUE))

data <- df_monthly$month_log_return
obs <-  nrow(df_monthly) - 1

get_n_moment(3, data)/sqrt(6/obs)
tseries::jarque.bera.test(data)
ks.test(data, "pnorm")
```

Based on tests' results we can reject the null about normality in both cases. But the distribution is symmetric.

